TY  - JOUR
T1  - Fictions: Legal and Organizational
AU  - Stanley, John D.
Y1  - 1966/06/01
PY  - 1966
DA  - 1966/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255030
DO  - 10.5465/255030
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 123
EP  - 126
VL  - 9
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article analyzes the role of organizational fictions, that are planned, within the formal authority structure, and deceive no one, because no one believes them to be true. An example might be the deference given to an owner's incompetent son-in-law, who is temporarily tolerated by the organization in order to achieve a long term goal. The article discusses legal fictions, scientific abstraction as negative fiction, possible managerial uses of quasi-legal fictions, ombudsman v. bureaucracy, and organizational fictions and their dangers. The author argues that these organizational fictions are necessary for the conduct of business.
